 that we\u2019re close to estimates in the end with regard to bunkers.  We consumed the small amount of 0.5% bunkers onboard on delivery and used 3.5% bunkers via the scrubber for the rest of the trip.  Not quite sure why but VMS assumes the vessels can use the scrubber in amazon river so there is about 120 mt LSGO consumption here that wasn\u2019t expected BUT surprisingly the price on the LSGO was cheaper than the HSFO so it actually helps the PnL a bit.  1 extra day laden steaming and 2 days waiting for bunkers off India make up the majority of extra time on the voyage.  Of the 4 add\u2019l days added only 0.5 days able to invoice on demurrage which drug down the TCE slightly.   0.44 days of offhire due to stop at Capetown for owners matters and scrubber breakdown issues.  \n1.\tNothing new here re: Amazon river but there is compulsory pilotage (approx. $160k USD round trip) and non-compulsory pilotage (approx. $60k USD each way).  This vessel/owner demanded the non-compulsory pilot inbound and her TCP states that we are only responsible for compulsory pilots.  That being said owners are pushing back on this one.  We\u2019re still awaiting the final invoice but this result assumes we will split the non-compulsory pilots 50/50.  \n              ** The vessel had the scrubber breakdown during the laden transit and ultimately class gave a dispensation to burn 3.5% bunkers without the scrubber in use.  We scrambled to procure some 0.5% bunkers at Manaus which was set to cost quite a bit of $$ but owners were able to get technicians on at river mouth and fix the scrubber before we got to Manaus.  Bunker desk able to cancel the stem without penalty and fingers crossed we don\u2019t see the scrubber issue rearing its ugly head again.\n                             --- 85 mt LSGO consumed in lieu of HSFO due to the scrubber issues but due to the fact the price was actually cheaper, we didn\u2019t claim this to the owner"}],"offhireList":[{"id":159915,"dateStartUtc":"2021-